\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mankiw2001sticky"

\end_inset

 argue that economic agents do not constantly update their expectations
 as it it is too costly to gather and process all information all the time.
 Due to this rational inattention, expectations are sticky.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "carroll2003"

\end_inset

 presents microfoundations for sticky prices holding that economic agents
 do not process economic data themselves.
 Households mostly lack the skills to form rational expectations, but their
 views derive from news reports of the views of professional forecasters,
 which in turn may be rational.
 However, as they do not pay attention to macroeconomic news all the time,
 expectations adapt only gradually.
 He shows that the gap between inflation expectations of experts and households
 is getting smaller due to the amount of media reporting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lamla2012"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lamla2008role"

\end_inset

 additionally consider how the tone of media coverage influences inflation
 expectations showing that the ‘tone’ of an article may bias expectations.
 If the reports exaggerate certain developments and are badly toned, more
 news may also bias expectations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If economic agents form their inflation expectations using news reports
 employing the latter for forecasting purposes is particularly appealing.
 In the best of all cases, survey results can be anticipated.
 News can be analyzed by humans following a code book to rate them according
 to the content.
 However, information in the media can be quantified employing automated
 models, as well.
 This presents an inexpensive and objective alternative.
 A simple but very effective approach in this respect is the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-word index counting the number of mentioning of the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

recession
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the Wall Street Journal and the New York Times (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Doms_et_al2004"

\end_inset

).
 Recently, more refined computer linguistic tools have been developed and
 applied to economic issues (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "uhl2011explaining"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite of its potential, outside financial markets, media data have been
 employed for forecasting only few variables (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "kholodilin2014media"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "uhl2011explaining,uhl2011reuters"

\end_inset

) and has, to the best of our knowledge, not been employed to forecast inflation.
 This paper aims at filling this gap contrasting the usefulness of media,
 both automatic indicators and indicators produced by humans, to a comprehensive
 set of alternative early indicators in a real-time forecast experiment
 for the prediciton German inflation.
 
\end_layout

