\begin_layout Section
Real-time experiment and evaluation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We replicate the forecast experiment of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "drechsel2012performance"

\end_inset

.
 In the first iteration, employing the data that would have been available
 in 2005:12 we estimate the autoregressive model and 179 models that include
 lagged variables of the endogenous and of one candidate variables each.
 For each of the horizons forecasted (1, 3, 6, and 12 months) we compute
 separate models.
 In the next iteration, we use the information available in 2006:01, and
 so on.
 Each iteration, we only make use of the last 60 months (rolling window
 approach).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The forecast errors are computed using inflation data as of 2015:04.
 For each model, the relative root mean squared forecast error (RMSFE) to
 the AR model is computed.
 In order to test the hypothesis of a candidate model performing equally
 good or worse than the AR we employ the test proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Clark_West_2007"

\end_inset

 that is applicable here, were the candidate models nest the AR.
 Finally, in order to make the comparison free of the choice of the benchmark,
 we employ the model confidence set (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "hansen2011model"

\end_inset

).
 It identifies a set of models, that can not be rejected as statistically
 inferior at certain confidence levels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:res-all"

\end_inset

 shows the results based on the forecasts for all periods from 2005:01 to
 2013:04 for 1, 3, 6, and 12 months horizons.
 The number of models out of the total of 180 models that are included in
 the MCS for each horizon is given in the second line.
 The results for the media models are presented in the lower part of the
 table.
 It shows the relative RMSFE of the respective models and the AR-process
 as a percentage of the latter, such that a value below (above) one implies
 a model with a lower RMSFE than the AR-process.
 Values smaller than one are printed in bold letters and two (one) stars
 indicate that the hypothesis of equal forecast performance of the AR and
 the respective model is rejected.
 For ease of presentation, only the results of media models included in
 the model confidence set are shown.
 As a reference, the results for the best non-media models for each period
 are shown in the upper part of the table.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The data allow to exclude about 50 percent of the models from the model
 confidence set for all periods.
 For the 1 month horizon forecasts the Media Tenor International index based
 on news items related to the business cycle (MTI cycle) ranks first having
 a relative RMSFE to the AR of 0.96 and the null of equal predictive performance
 is rejected at the 5 percent level.
 For the 3 and 6 months horizon forecasts, the automatic sentiment indicator
 based on all articles of the economic section in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\shape italic
Die Zeit
\shape default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is the best model.
 Its relative RMSFE implying an improvement of 11 and 6 percent respectively.
 However, the null of equal predictive forecast accuracy is rejected at
 the 5 percent level only in case of the 6 months horizon forecasts.
 For the 12 months horizon forecasts, the best media model is again MTI
 cycle, ranking second.
 Its relative RMSFE of 0.83 is very close to the best non-media model, the
 unemployment rate, and the null of equal forecast accuracy compared to
 the AR model is rejected at the 5 percent level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The count indexes using Genios data and the those that use the subindexes
 of the news items related to inflation are performing comparatively poorly
 ranking 37nd at best (in the case of Genios for 6 months horizon forecasts).
 The Mediatenor index based on all news items related to inflation ranks
 second for one months horizon forecasts.
 However, the null of equal forecast accuracy compared to the AR can not
 be rejected at conventional levels.
 
\end_layout

